{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019ufyyaUURgJDBokpw3hcGy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. Looking at the precondition logic:\n\n1. `es_env_ready` probe: checks if there are Running pods in elasticsearch namespace. Since there ARE running pods, this probe SUCCEEDS → apply is skipped (on_probe_fail: skip means it only runs apply if probe FAILS).\n\nWait, `on_probe_fail: skip` means: if the probe FAILS, SKIP the entire unit (don't run apply). If the probe PASSES, apply IS run.\n\nActually, let me re-read the KARMA architecture... `on_probe_fail: skip` means: on probe failure, skip the apply. If probe passes, run apply.\nHmm, actually I think the semantics are reversed: probe passes means the setup is already done so skip apply, but probe fails means we need to set up so run apply. Looking at the elasticsearch probe that counts Running pods—since there are 11 Running pods, the probe passes, which means `on_probe_fail: skip` should skip the apply step since the environment is already ready. probe fails, the unit gets skipped entirely. For `transform_scenario_fixture`, there's a similar pattern where the probe checks if the transform already exists and skips if it does.\n\nLooking at the actual probe logs, both checks passed—the Elasticsearch pods were running and the transform returned HTTP 200—which means neither unit's apply block actually ran.\n\nBut that's strange because the transform shouldn't exist yet. Let me figure out what status code Elasticsearch actually returns when querying a non-existent transform's stats endpoint.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5339,"cache_read_input_tokens":37042,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5339},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}