{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01S9ioWQJ6jsQ1UdGL8uj6TP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. `es-transform-0` is an **ingest-only** node (role: `i` = ingest). It's a dedicated node for transforms.\n2. The \"transform capacity\" means having `es-transform-0` running so the transform can be assigned to it.\n3. The scenario fault is: scaling `es-transform` to 0 replicas (removing the ingest/transform capacity node).\n\nBut currently, `es-transform-0` IS running (we can see it in the pod list). The issue is that the transform itself doesn't exist!\nLooking at the node configuration, I see that `es-transform-0` is configured with the ingest role, while the main cluster nodes have master, data, and ingest roles. In Elasticsearch 7.17, transforms need either a dedicated transform role or will run on any eligible node if no dedicated transform node exists. The `es-transform` StatefulSet appears to only have the ingest role configured, which might be the mismatch here. Looking at the test case more carefully, the precondition scales the `es-transform` StatefulSet down to zero replicas to simulate the fault condition. The transform job was running on that node, so removing it should cause the transform to stop. But I'm realizing there's a mismatch here—if the `es-transform` node only has the ingest role and transforms in ES 7.17 require either a dedicated transform role or fall back to data/master nodes, then this node shouldn't have been running the transform in the first place.\n\nLet me trace through what the test scenario actually expects: the transform `events-by-service` should exist and be running, the source index `app-events` should have data, and the destination index `app-events-rollup` should be tracking checkpoints. Right now none of those exist, which means the precondition setup is incomplete. The precondition check passed even though the tra